(6, 3, E'# LensBook: The All-in-One Booking Platform for Freelance Photographers\n\n## 1. Executive Summary\n\nLensBook is a purpose-built scheduling and client management platform for freelance photographers. Unlike generic booking tools, LensBook integrates session scheduling, automated client communication, contract e-signing, and proof delivery into one cohesive workflow. The platform targets freelance photographers handling 15–40 sessions per month who currently juggle 3–5 disconnected tools. By consolidating the entire client lifecycle from initial inquiry to final gallery delivery, LensBook reduces administrative overhead by an estimated 60% and cuts no-show rates by up to 35% through automated reminders. The business model is SaaS with tiered monthly subscriptions ($19/$49/$99), projecting $1.2M ARR within 24 months of launch.\n\n## 2. Market Analysis\n\n| Metric | Value | Source / Notes |\n|---|---|---|\n| US freelance photographers | ~260,000 | IBISWorld 2024 |\n| UK freelance photographers | ~42,000 | ONS Labour Survey 2023 |\n| Avg. sessions per month (active) | 22 | Internal survey, n=180 |\n| Avg. revenue per session | $285 | PhotoShelter Industry Report 2024 |\n| Time spent on admin per week | 9.4 hrs | Survey respondents |\n| Willingness to pay for booking tool | 68% | Survey, price point $20–$60/mo |\n| TAM (US + UK) | ~$186M/yr | 302K photographers × $51.50 avg spend |\n| SAM (active, 15+ sessions/mo) | ~$74M/yr | Top 40% segment |\n| SOM Year 2 target | $1.2M ARR | 2,000 paying users × $50 ARPU |\n\n## 3. Competitive Landscape\n\n| Competitor | Strengths | Weaknesses | Pricing |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| HoneyBook | All-in-one CRM, polished UI | Expensive, overkill for small photographers | $19–$79/mo |\n| Pixieset | Excellent gallery delivery | No scheduling, no contracts | $8–$32/mo |\n| Calendly | Slick scheduling UX | No photography-specific workflow | $0–$16/mo |\n| ShootProof | Strong proofing & print sales | Clunky booking, poor mobile | $10–$35/mo |\n| 17hats | Full CRM suite | Steep learning curve | $45/mo |\n| **LensBook** | Photography-first, integrated workflow | New entrant, brand awareness | $19–$99/mo |\n\n## 4. Target User Personas\n\n**Persona 1 — Jake, 29, Wedding & Portrait Photographer, Austin TX**\nJake shoots 28 sessions/month averaging $320/session. He uses Google Calendar, Gmail, Dropbox, and DocuSign separately. He loses 2–3 hours daily switching between apps, frequently forgets follow-up emails, and has had 4 no-shows in the past month alone. He wants one place to see his entire schedule, automate client reminders, and deliver proofs without uploading to yet another service.\n\n**Persona 2 — Melissa, 38, Commercial & Event Photographer, London UK**\nMelissa runs a solo photography business with a part-time assistant. She handles 18–22 sessions/month and charges £280–£650 per shoot. Her pain points are managing international client time zones, issuing invoices promptly, and following up on proof selections that drag out for weeks. She values professionalism—her clients are small businesses—so she needs branded client portals and formal contract workflows.\n\n**Persona 3 — Tyler, 24, Newborn & Family Photographer, Denver CO**\nTyler is 18 months into his business and overwhelmed by administration. He has no CRM, sends invoices via PayPal, and delivers proofs through Google Photos links he emails manually. He needs an affordable, easy-to-start solution that grows with him. His budget is under $25/month.\n\n## 5. Core Features\n\n| Priority | Feature | Description |\n|---|---|---|\n| P0 | Smart Booking Calendar | Real-time availability, buffer times, travel radius blocks |\n| P0 | Automated Client Reminders | SMS + email at 72hr / 24hr / 2hr before session |\n| P0 | Contract E-Sign | Templated contracts, legally binding e-signature |\n| P0 | Online Payment Collection | Stripe integration, deposit + balance invoicing |\n| P0 | Proof Gallery Delivery | Password-protected galleries, client selection & download |\n| P1 | Client Portal | Branded portal for communication history, documents, galleries |\n| P1 | Session Type Templates | Define shoot types with pricing, duration, add-ons |\n| P1 | Lead Inquiry Form | Embeddable form → auto-creates draft booking |\n| P1 | Revenue Dashboard | Monthly/quarterly earnings, booking trends |\n| P2 | Automated Follow-Up Sequences | Post-shoot review request, referral nudge |\n| P2 | Multi-Photographer Team Mode | Sub-accounts, session assignment, shared calendar |\n| P2 | Print Sales Integration | Upsell prints via gallery, fulfillment via WHCC/ProDPI |\n\n## 6. Technical Architecture\n\n**Frontend**: Next.js 14 (App Router) + TailwindCSS — SSR for client portals, SPA for photographer dashboard. Mobile-first responsive design.\n\n**Backend**: Node.js + Express API (REST), PostgreSQL for relational data (bookings, clients, contracts), S3-compatible object storage (Cloudflare R2) for proof galleries.\n\n**Key Services**:\n- **Scheduler**: Bull queue (Redis-backed) for time-sensitive reminder jobs\n- **Payments**: Stripe Connect — photographers onboard as connected accounts, platform takes 0.5% per transaction on paid tiers\n- **E-Sign**: DocuSign API (Enterprise plan) or HelloSign depending on tier\n- **Image Delivery**: CloudFront CDN in front of R2, watermark generation via Sharp (Node)\n- **Notifications**: Twilio (SMS) + SendGrid (email)\n\n**Infrastructure**: AWS ECS Fargate (auto-scaling), RDS PostgreSQL, ElastiCache Redis, deployed via Terraform. SOC 2 Type I target at 12 months.\n\n## 7. Business Model\n\n| Plan | Price | Features | Target User |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Starter | $19/mo | 20 sessions/mo, 5GB gallery storage, basic contracts | Tyler (new photographers) |\n| Pro | $49/mo | Unlimited sessions, 50GB storage, full automation, client portal | Jake (established solo) |\n| Studio | $99/mo | Everything + 3 sub-accounts, 200GB, print sales, priority support | Melissa (small studio) |\n| Transaction fee | 0.5% | On all payments processed (Pro+) | — |\n\nProjected revenue mix at 2,000 users: 40% Starter ($15K/mo), 45% Pro ($44K/mo), 15% Studio ($30K/mo) = ~$89K MRR = ~$1.07M ARR.\n\n## 8. MVP Roadmap\n\n| Milestone | Timeline | Deliverables |\n|---|---|---|\n| M1 | Months 1–2 | Booking calendar, session types, availability management, basic email reminders |\n| M2 | Months 3–4 | Contract templates + e-sign, Stripe payments, proof gallery upload & share |\n| M3 | Months 5–6 | Client portal, lead inquiry form, SMS reminders via Twilio, revenue dashboard |\n| M4 | Months 7–8 | Mobile app (React Native), print sales integration, team mode, referral program |\n\n## 9. Success Metrics\n\n| KPI | Month 3 Target | Month 6 Target | Month 12 Target |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Paying users | 150 | 500 | 2,000 |\n| MRR | $5,500 | $22,000 | $89,000 |\n| Avg. sessions booked per user/mo | 18 | 21 | 24 |\n| No-show rate reduction (vs. baseline) | 15% | 28% | 35% |\n| Gallery delivery time (median) | < 5 days | < 4 days | < 3 days |\n| NPS score | ≥ 40 | ≥ 50 | ≥ 60 |\n| Churn (monthly) | < 8% | < 6% | < 4% |\n\n## 10. Risks & Mitigation\n\n| Risk | Likelihood | Impact | Mitigation |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| HoneyBook launches photography-specific tier | Medium | High | Accelerate niche features (proof selection, watermarking) that HoneyBook lacks |\n| Photographers resistant to switching tools | High | High | Offer free data import from HoneyBook, Pixieset, 17hats; white-glove onboarding |\n| S3 storage costs exceed projections | Medium | Medium | Cap gallery retention at 12 months on Starter; enforce storage alerts |\n| Payment disputes / chargebacks | Low | Medium | Stripe Radar integration; require signed contracts before payment |\n| GDPR compliance for UK clients | Medium | High | EU data residency option (Frankfurt region), GDPR-compliant data processing agreements |\n', '[{"step":"market_research","decision":"Focus on US + UK markets only for MVP","reason":"Regulatory complexity in EU without GDPR infrastructure; US+UK share language and similar payment infrastructure"},{"step":"feature_scoping","decision":"Include proof gallery delivery in P0","reason":"User interviews showed 78% of photographers cite gallery delivery as top pain point; excluding it reduces differentiation"},{"step":"tech_stack","decision":"Node.js over Go for backend","reason":"Faster iteration speed; larger talent pool; existing npm ecosystem for image processing (Sharp)"},{"step":"pricing","decision":"Set Pro tier at $49 not $39","reason":"Competitor analysis showed HoneyBook at $79 with weaker photography features; $49 positions as premium-affordable"},{"step":"mvp_scope","decision":"Defer mobile app to M4","reason":"85% of photographer admin happens on desktop; mobile can follow after core web product validated"}]',
 'submitted', 42, NOW() - INTERVAL '28 days', NOW() - INTERVAL '29 days', NOW() - INTERVAL '28 days'),

(6, 8, E'# ShootSchedule: Lightweight Booking Engine for Solo Photographers\n\n## 1. Executive Summary\n\nShootSchedule is a minimalist, mobile-first booking and workflow tool designed for freelance photographers who want simplicity over feature bloat. The core thesis is that most photographers are overwhelmed by existing CRM platforms—they need 20% of the features that cover 80% of their daily workflow: a reliable calendar, client-facing booking links, automatic reminders, and a clean way to share proofs. ShootSchedule ships these essentials with a one-time setup of under 15 minutes, targeting photographers booking 15–40 sessions/month at an accessible $15/month price point. The business model is freemium-to-paid, with a free tier limited to 8 sessions/month as the primary acquisition channel. Targeting 5,000 MAU and $600K ARR by end of Year 2.\n\n## 2. Market Analysis\n\n| Metric | Value | Source |\n|---|---|---|\n| Freelance photographers in US | ~258,000 | BLS Occupational Outlook 2024 |\n| Average annual revenue (solo photographer) | ~$41,200 | IBISWorld Photography Services 2024 |\n| % using dedicated booking software | 31% | ShootProof survey 2023 |\n| % using Google Calendar + email only | 44% | ShootProof survey 2023 |\n| Mobile usage for business tasks (photographers) | 71% | Sprout Social SMB study 2024 |\n| Average no-show rate without reminders | 18% | Internal benchmark from beta users |\n| Revenue lost to no-shows annually (avg photographer) | ~$3,200 | 18% × $41,200 × 0.43 sessions |\n| Addressable market (31%+ tool adoption) | ~$93M | Conservative SAM estimate |\n\n## 3. Competitive Landscape\n\n| Competitor | Monthly Price | Key Weakness | ShootSchedule Advantage |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| HoneyBook | $19–$79 | Complex onboarding (avg 4hrs to set up) | 15-min setup, opinionated defaults |\n| Calendly | $0–$16 | No photography workflow, no proofs | Integrated proof sharing + payments |\n| Acuity Scheduling | $16–$49 | Generic, not photography-specific | Session type templates pre-built |\n| Pixieset | $8–$32 | No booking or contracts, gallery only | Full workflow in one tool |\n| Google Workspace | ~$6 | Manual everything, zero automation | Automated reminders, contracts |\n| **ShootSchedule** | $0–$15 | — | Simple, fast, photography-first |\n\n## 4. Target User Personas\n\n**Persona 1 — Cody, 26, Portrait & Lifestyle Photographer, Nashville TN**\nCody shoots 20–25 sessions/month for individuals and small families. He is technically capable but time-poor, booking clients via Instagram DMs and invoicing via Venmo. He has lost $1,800 in the past quarter to no-shows and late cancellations with no deposit policy. He wants a solution that''s ready to use in an afternoon without watching tutorial videos.\n\n**Persona 2 — Rachel, 44, School & Sports Photographer, Manchester UK**\nRachel manages a high volume of repeat bookings—schools hire her seasonally, which means her booking peaks are intense but predictable. She currently manages everything in spreadsheets. Her pain point is communication: parents miss proof deadlines, schools need invoices fast. She needs bulk scheduling and proof collection more than CRM sophistication. Budget: £12–£18/month.\n\n## 5. Core Features\n\n| Priority | Feature | Description |\n|---|---|---|\n| P0 | Booking Link Generator | Shareable URL with availability calendar; clients self-book |\n| P0 | Session Type Setup | Pre-built templates (portrait, wedding, event, school); custom add-ons |\n| P0 | SMS + Email Reminders | Auto-send at 48hr and 2hr; customizable message templates |\n| P0 | Deposit Collection | Stripe-powered; configurable deposit % or flat fee at booking |\n| P0 | Proof Gallery Share | Upload and share password-protected gallery link via SMS/email |\n| P1 | Contract Templates | 3 pre-built contracts (portrait, commercial, event); digital sign |\n| P1 | Client Profile History | All sessions, payments, galleries per client in one view |\n| P1 | Buffer Time Rules | Auto-block between sessions for travel/editing |\n| P1 | Cancellation Policy Enforcement | Auto-email cancel policy; hold deposit on late cancel |\n| P2 | Bulk Scheduling Mode | Upload CSV of school/event bookings; auto-create sessions |\n| P2 | Review Request Automation | 3-day post-delivery email with Google Review link |\n\n## 6. Technical Architecture\n\n**Philosophy**: Lean, serverless-first to minimize operational overhead at early scale.\n\n**Frontend**: Next.js 14 with App Router. Static pages for public booking links (edge-cached via Vercel). Dynamic dashboard for photographers.\n\n**Backend**: Vercel Edge Functions for lightweight endpoints; PlanetScale (MySQL-compatible) for relational data. Redis (Upstash) for job queuing.\n\n**Notifications**: Postmark (email, high deliverability) + Twilio Verify (SMS reminders). Reminder jobs triggered by cron via Inngest.\n\n**Payments**: Stripe Checkout — simple hosted payment page, no PCI scope on our infrastructure.\n\n**File Storage**: Cloudflare R2 for gallery images (zero egress cost), served via signed URLs with 30-day expiry.\n\n**Authentication**: Magic link email auth (no password friction for clients); Clerk for photographer accounts.\n\n## 7. Business Model\n\n| Plan | Price | Session Limit | Key Restriction |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Free | $0/mo | 8 sessions/mo | No contracts, 2GB storage, ShootSchedule branding |\n| Solo | $15/mo | Unlimited | Removes branding, adds contracts + SMS reminders |\n| Pro | $29/mo | Unlimited | +bulk scheduling, advanced analytics, priority support |\n\nFunnel assumption: 15% free-to-paid conversion. At 5,000 MAU: 750 paid (600 Solo, 150 Pro) = $13,500 MRR = $162K ARR Year 1. Year 2 at 20K MAU with improved conversion: $648K ARR.\n\n## 8. MVP Roadmap\n\n| Milestone | Timeline | Deliverables |\n|---|---|---|\n| M1 | Months 1–2 | Booking link, session types, availability calendar, Stripe deposits |\n| M2 | Months 3–4 | SMS/email reminders, proof gallery upload, client history view |\n| M3 | Months 5–6 | Contract templates + e-sign, cancellation enforcement, review automation |\n| M4 | Months 7–9 | Bulk scheduling, analytics dashboard, iOS/Android PWA improvements |\n\n## 9. Success Metrics\n\n| KPI | M3 | M6 | M12 |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Registered photographers | 800 | 2,500 | 8,000 |\n| MAU | 400 | 1,500 | 5,000 |\n| Paid subscribers | 60 | 300 | 1,000 |\n| MRR | $1,200 | $5,500 | $18,500 |\n| Free-to-paid conversion | 10% | 13% | 15% |\n| Avg. setup time (new user) | < 20 min | < 15 min | < 12 min |\n| No-show rate (platform avg) | 10% | 8% | 6% |\n\n## 10. Risks & Mitigation\n\n| Risk | Likelihood | Impact | Mitigation |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Low free-to-paid conversion | High | High | Aggressive session cap at 8/mo; highlight ROI ($3,200 no-show cost) in upgrade prompt |\n| Twilio SMS costs at scale | Medium | Medium | Negotiate volume pricing at 50K+ SMS/mo; offer email-only tier for cost-sensitive users |\n| PlanetScale pricing changes | Low | Medium | Design data layer to be portable; evaluate Neon.tech as fallback |\n| Feature parity gap vs. HoneyBook | Medium | Low | Intentionally stay simple; market as "HoneyBook alternative for photographers who hate CRMs" |\n| GDPR compliance for UK/EU users | Medium | High | Data residency in EU (Cloudflare R2 EU region); DPA template for pro users |\n', '[{"step":"positioning","decision":"Lead with simplicity as core differentiator","reason":"User research showed 62% of target photographers abandoned HoneyBook during onboarding due to complexity"},{"step":"pricing","decision":"Cap free tier at 8 sessions per month not 5","reason":"8 sessions/mo is enough to validate value but creates natural upgrade pressure for active photographers"},{"step":"tech_stack","decision":"Choose serverless (Vercel + PlanetScale) over traditional VPS","reason":"Team of 2; serverless eliminates DevOps overhead at early stage; scale cost is linear"},{"step":"auth","decision":"Magic link for client-facing flows","reason":"Clients should never need to create an account; friction kills proof delivery completion rates"},{"step":"storage","decision":"Cloudflare R2 over AWS S3","reason":"Zero egress fees critical for gallery delivery; photographers upload/download large files frequently"}]',
 'submitted', 38, NOW() - INTERVAL '25 days', NOW() - INTERVAL '26 days', NOW() - INTERVAL '25 days'),

(6, 20, E'# FrameFlow: Photographer Business OS with AI Scheduling Intelligence\n\n## 1. Executive Summary\n\nFrameFlow reimagines freelance photographer operations as a unified "business OS" that combines intelligent scheduling with AI-assisted client communication and post-production workflow management. The platform''s unique value proposition is its AI layer: an assistant trained on photography business patterns that drafts client emails, suggests optimal session spacing based on travel time and editing backlog, and flags at-risk clients who haven''t responded to proof galleries. FrameFlow targets mid-to-high-volume photographers (20–40 sessions/month) who have outgrown simple booking tools but find full CRMs like HoneyBook overly complex for a solo operation. Priced at $39/month (single tier, all features), FrameFlow projects $2M ARR within 30 months.\n\n## 2. Market Analysis\n\n| Metric | Value | Notes |\n|---|---|---|\n| US professional photographers (full-time) | ~85,000 | BLS 2024 full-time classification |\n| US photographers 20+ sessions/month | ~52,000 | Top 20% by volume |\n| Average revenue per photographer (top 20%) | ~$78,000/yr | PhotoShelter Pro Income Survey |\n| Admin time as % of work hours | 23% | Survey n=240 active photographers |\n| Dollar value of admin time (avg) | ~$17,940/yr | 23% × $78K |\n| AI assistant willingness-to-pay premium | +$12/mo | vs. non-AI equivalent tool |\n| TAM for AI-powered photography tools | ~$210M | US market, photography software |\n| SOM 30-month target | $2M ARR | ~4,300 paying users |\n\n## 3. Competitive Landscape\n\n| Competitor | AI Features | Scheduling | Proof Delivery | Price |\n|---|---|---|---|---|\n| HoneyBook | Basic smart fields only | Yes | No | $19–$79/mo |\n| Studio Ninja | None | Yes | No | $10–$25/mo |\n| Táve | None | Yes, complex | No | $21–$72/mo |\n| Pixieset | None | No | Yes (best-in-class) | $8–$32/mo |\n| Light Blue | None | Yes | No | £10–£20/mo |\n| **FrameFlow** | AI email drafts, backlog alerts, scheduling intelligence | Yes | Yes | $39/mo |\n\n## 4. Target User Personas\n\n**Persona 1 — Diana, 35, Wedding Photographer, Charleston SC**\nDiana shoots 3–4 weddings/month plus 12–15 portrait sessions. Her revenue exceeds $120K/year but she works 60+ hours weekly. The gap in her workflow is post-shoot: she drafts the same client update emails repeatedly, forgets to follow up on gallery selections, and routinely squeezes sessions too close together leaving no editing buffer. An AI that drafts her emails and warns her when her editing queue is unsustainable would save her 6+ hours weekly.\n\n**Persona 2 — Marcus, 41, Commercial Photographer, Chicago IL**\nMarcus handles product shoots and corporate headshots—30+ sessions/month with diverse clients including brands, agencies, and law firms. His challenge is client communication tone: corporate clients expect formal, prompt correspondence. He wants AI that learns his communication style and drafts professional emails he can approve with one click, rather than typing from scratch each time.\n\n**Persona 3 — Fiona, 29, Newborn & Maternity Photographer, Edinburgh UK**\nFiona is meticulously organized but struggles with the human side: following up with clients who ghost her proof galleries. She loses £1,200–£1,800/quarter on uncollected print orders. An automated follow-up sequence with AI-personalized messages would materially improve her revenue capture.\n\n## 5. Core Features\n\n| Priority | Feature | Description |\n|---|---|---|\n| P0 | AI Email Assistant | Drafts context-aware client emails; learns photographer''s tone over 30 days |\n| P0 | Intelligent Scheduling | Suggests session slots considering travel time, editing backlog, energy reserves |\n| P0 | Booking Calendar | Full self-booking with availability sync (Google Cal, iCal) |\n| P0 | Contract + Payment | E-sign contracts; Stripe deposits and final balance billing |\n| P0 | Proof Gallery Delivery | Client-facing gallery with selection, download, print order upsell |\n| P1 | Editing Backlog Tracker | Log editing hours per session; AI alerts when queue exceeds 3-day buffer |\n| P1 | At-Risk Client Alerts | Flags clients who haven''t opened gallery within 72hrs; suggests re-engagement |\n| P1 | Communication History | Full thread of all emails/SMSes per client, AI-searchable |\n| P1 | Revenue Forecasting | 60-day forward revenue projection based on booked + pipeline sessions |\n| P2 | Style Profile Learning | AI identifies photographer''s communication patterns from email history import |\n| P2 | Referral Tracking | Source attribution for new clients; identify top referrers |\n| P2 | Vendor Integrations | WHCC, ProDPI print fulfillment; direct lab order from gallery |\n\n## 6. Technical Architecture\n\n**AI Layer**: OpenAI GPT-4o fine-tuned on photographer communication datasets (anonymized, opt-in). Prompt engineering layer extracts session context (client name, shoot type, outstanding items) to produce personalized email drafts. User feedback loop (approve/edit/reject) fine-tunes per-user style profile over time.\n\n**Backend**: Go 1.23 + Echo v4 REST API. PostgreSQL 16 for structured data. Redis for session state and job queuing. S3 + CloudFront for gallery delivery.\n\n**Frontend**: Next.js 14 App Router + TailwindCSS. Real-time editing backlog dashboard via WebSocket (Go gorilla/websocket).\n\n**Scheduling Intelligence Engine**: Custom algorithm considering geo-distance between session locations (Google Maps Distance Matrix API), historical editing time per session type, and photographer-defined energy/availability preferences.\n\n**Infrastructure**: DigitalOcean App Platform (managed), managed PostgreSQL, Spaces for object storage. Terraform for IaC.\n\n## 7. Business Model\n\n| Stream | Description | Projected Contribution |\n|---|---|---|\n| Subscription ($39/mo) | Single all-inclusive tier | 85% of revenue |\n| Print sales commission | 8% of print order value via lab integration | 10% of revenue |\n| AI credits overage | >500 AI email drafts/mo = $5 per 100 additional | 5% of revenue |\n\nAt 4,300 subscribers: $200K MRR from subscriptions + ~$24K from print commissions = ~$2.7M ARR.\n\n## 8. MVP Roadmap\n\n| Milestone | Timeline | Deliverables |\n|---|---|---|\n| M1 | Months 1–3 | Core booking calendar, contracts, Stripe payments, proof gallery |\n| M2 | Months 4–5 | AI email drafts (GPT-4o integration), editing backlog tracker |\n| M3 | Months 6–7 | Intelligent scheduling engine, at-risk client alerts, revenue forecasting |\n| M4 | Months 8–10 | Style profile learning, print lab integration, referral tracking, mobile PWA |\n\n## 9. Success Metrics\n\n| KPI | M6 | M12 | M24 |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Paying subscribers | 300 | 1,200 | 4,300 |\n| MRR | $11,700 | $46,800 | $167,700 |\n| AI emails drafted per user/mo (avg) | 45 | 60 | 75 |\n| AI email approval rate (no edits) | 55% | 65% | 72% |\n| Editing backlog overrun rate | < 15% | < 10% | < 7% |\n| Gallery uncollected rate | < 12% | < 8% | < 5% |\n| Monthly churn | < 5% | < 4% | < 3% |\n\n## 10. Risks & Mitigation\n\n| Risk | Likelihood | Impact | Mitigation |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| OpenAI API cost at scale | High | High | Negotiate volume pricing; explore open-source model (Llama 3) for style profiling |\n| AI email quality below expectations | Medium | High | Human-in-the-loop always; position as "draft assistant" not "auto-send" |\n| Single pricing tier limits entry | Medium | Medium | Monitor conversion data; introduce $19 Lite tier if CAC too high |\n| Scheduling engine accuracy in rural areas | Low | Medium | Fall back to manual scheduling; Maps API distance matrix covers 98% of US addresses |\n| Data privacy concerns with AI training | Medium | High | Explicit opt-in for style learning; never use client data for model training |\n', '[{"step":"differentiation","decision":"Build AI email assistant as core P0 feature","reason":"No competitor offers AI-native communication; this is the fastest path to ''10x better'' product perception"},{"step":"pricing","decision":"Single tier at $39 over tiered model","reason":"Simplicity reduces decision fatigue; $39 is above Starter but below HoneyBook Pro — clear value position"},{"step":"ai_model","decision":"GPT-4o with per-user fine-tuning over generic prompts","reason":"Generic AI emails feel impersonal; per-user style learning is the moat competitors cannot quickly replicate"},{"step":"scheduling_engine","decision":"Build custom algorithm over off-the-shelf scheduling library","reason":"Editing backlog + travel time + energy preferences combination is unique; no existing library handles all three"},{"step":"backend","decision":"Go backend for scheduling engine","reason":"Scheduling intelligence requires concurrent computation; Go goroutines handle this efficiently vs. Node.js single thread"}]',
 'submitted', 55, NOW() - INTERVAL '22 days', NOW() - INTERVAL '23 days', NOW() - INTERVAL '22 days'),

