(7, 5, E'# BloomAlert: Holiday Promotion Automation for Local Florists\n\n## 1. Executive Summary\n\nBloomAlert is a dedicated holiday promotion and customer retention platform for independent florist shops. Local florists consistently lose seasonal revenue to 1-800-Flowers and FTD because they lack automated marketing infrastructure. BloomAlert closes this gap by automatically identifying upcoming holidays, generating personalized bouquet recommendations based on each customer''s purchase history, and dispatching promotional emails and SMS reminders on optimal send schedules. The platform requires zero marketing expertise to operate—setup takes 30 minutes and runs autonomously thereafter. Target customers are independent florist shops with 200–2,000 customer records, priced at $29/month. Projected to reach 1,500 shops and $522K ARR by end of Year 2.\n\n## 2. Market Analysis\n\n| Metric | Value | Source |\n|---|---|---|\n| US independent florist shops | ~19,000 | IBIS World Florists Industry Report 2024 |\n| UK independent florist shops | ~6,500 | Flowers & Plants Association 2023 |\n| Average seasonal revenue uplift (with promos) | +28% | SAF (Society of American Florists) |\n| Top 5 revenue holidays | Valentine''s Day, Mother''s Day, Christmas, Thanksgiving, Easter | SAF Seasonal Report |\n| Valentine''s Day revenue share (of annual) | 18–24% | SAF |\n| % of florists with email marketing capability | 34% | Mailchimp SMB floristry benchmark |\n| Revenue lost to national chains per shop/yr | ~$12,400 | Estimated local market share loss |\n| Willingness to pay for promo automation | 61% | Phone survey, n=85 florist owners |\n\n## 3. Competitive Landscape\n\n| Competitor | Type | Weakness for Florists | BloomAlert Advantage |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Mailchimp | Generic email marketing | Manual campaign creation; no holiday intelligence | Auto holiday calendar; bouquet-specific templates |\n| Klaviyo | E-commerce email | Too complex; requires e-commerce store | Works with any POS data; no store required |\n| Constant Contact | Generic email | No SMS; no personalization | SMS + email; purchase-history personalization |\n| Podium | Review + messaging | Expensive ($300+/mo); no promos | 10x cheaper; promo-focused |\n| BloomNation | Marketplace | Takes 20–30% commission; loses customer relationship | Owned channel; zero commission |\n| **BloomAlert** | Florist-specific promo | New entrant | Holiday intelligence + purchase-history targeting |\n\n## 4. Target User Personas\n\n**Persona 1 — Sarah, 48, Flower Shop Owner, Brooklyn NY**\nSarah has run her corner flower shop for 14 years with 3 part-time employees. She has 1,800 past customer email addresses in her Square POS but has never used them for marketing. Every Valentine''s Day she watches walk-in traffic thin out as customers buy from FTD online. She''s not tech-savvy but knows she''s leaving money on the table. She needs a tool that works without her having to learn marketing.\n\n**Persona 2 — Graham, 55, Florist & Wedding Specialist, Bath UK**\nGraham operates a boutique florist with a strong wedding clientele. He has 600 recurring customers who buy for birthdays and anniversaries. He currently hand-writes postcards before Christmas—charming but unscalable. He wants to automate seasonal promotions without losing the personal feel. Budget: £20–£30/month.\n\n## 5. Core Features\n\n| Priority | Feature | Description |\n|---|---|---|\n| P0 | Holiday Calendar Engine | Pre-loaded US + UK holiday schedule; auto-triggers campaigns 7, 3, 1 day before |\n| P0 | Customer Import | CSV or Square/Clover/Shopify POS sync; maps customer purchase history |\n| P0 | Personalized Email Campaigns | Auto-generates emails referencing last purchase; "You loved tulips in March—here''s a Valentine''s special" |\n| P0 | SMS Promo Reminders | Day-before and day-of text alerts; opt-in managed automatically |\n| P0 | Pre-Built Bouquet Templates | 40+ seasonal email templates with product image slots |\n| P1 | Coupon Code Generator | Unique per-customer discount codes, redeemable in-store or online |\n| P1 | Campaign Analytics | Open rate, click rate, coupon redemption, estimated revenue attributed |\n| P1 | Customer Segmentation | High-value customers, lapsed (no purchase > 6 months), wedding clients |\n| P1 | Birthday & Anniversary Reminders | Auto-detect repeat purchase dates; send advance reminder |\n| P2 | Online Order Link | Direct "Order Now" CTA linking to florist''s existing website or Square Online |\n| P2 | Multi-Location Support | Chain florists with 2–5 locations, per-store customer lists |\n| P2 | Postcard Mailer Integration | Via Lob API; physical postcard for premium customers |\n\n## 6. Technical Architecture\n\n**Backend**: Python 3.12 + FastAPI. PostgreSQL for customer and campaign data. Celery + Redis for scheduled campaign dispatch jobs.\n\n**Email**: SendGrid Marketing API — transactional and marketing in one account; handles unsubscribes automatically per CAN-SPAM/GDPR.\n\n**SMS**: Twilio Messaging Services with compliance-first opt-in flow; double opt-in for UK users per PECR regulations.\n\n**POS Integrations**: Square API (OAuth), Clover webhooks, Shopify (Customer API). CSV import fallback for any POS.\n\n**Personalization Engine**: Rule-based matching (last product category → seasonal equivalent recommendation). No ML required at MVP; statistical matching achieves 74% relevance accuracy in beta.\n\n**Frontend**: React + Vite (SPA). Simple campaign preview, schedule view, and analytics dashboard. Mobile-responsive but desktop-primary.\n\n**Infrastructure**: Railway.app for API + worker deployment; Neon for PostgreSQL; minimal DevOps burden for 2-person team.\n\n## 7. Business Model\n\n| Plan | Monthly Price | Customer Contacts | Key Features |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Starter | $29/mo | Up to 500 contacts | Email only, 5 holidays/yr, basic templates |\n| Growth | $59/mo | Up to 2,000 contacts | Email + SMS, all holidays, segmentation, analytics |\n| Pro | $99/mo | Up to 10,000 contacts | Everything + multi-location, postcard mailer, API access |\n\nAdditional SMS: $0.015/message beyond included volume (200 SMS/mo on Growth).\n\n## 8. MVP Roadmap\n\n| Milestone | Timeline | Deliverables |\n|---|---|---|\n| M1 | Months 1–2 | Customer CSV import, holiday calendar engine, email campaign templates, basic send scheduling |\n| M2 | Months 3–4 | Square POS integration, personalization engine v1, unsubscribe management, open/click analytics |\n| M3 | Months 5–6 | SMS via Twilio, coupon code generation, customer segmentation, birthday/anniversary triggers |\n| M4 | Months 7–8 | Shopify + Clover integrations, multi-location, postcard API, revenue attribution dashboard |\n\n## 9. Success Metrics\n\n| KPI | M3 | M6 | M24 |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Paying florist shops | 80 | 300 | 1,500 |\n| MRR | $2,800 | $14,000 | $43,500 |\n| Average campaign open rate | > 28% | > 32% | > 35% |\n| Coupon redemption rate | > 8% | > 12% | > 15% |\n| Seasonal revenue uplift (per shop) | +12% | +20% | +28% |\n| NPS | ≥ 45 | ≥ 55 | ≥ 65 |\n| Monthly churn | < 6% | < 4% | < 3% |\n\n## 10. Risks & Mitigation\n\n| Risk | Likelihood | Impact | Mitigation |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Florists don''t have clean customer data | High | High | Offer free data cleaning tool at onboarding; CSV template with de-duplication |\n| SMS opt-in compliance errors (TCPA/PECR) | Medium | High | Double opt-in enforced at platform level; legal review before SMS launch |\n| Seasonal revenue concentrated in Q1/Q4 | Medium | Medium | Build churn buffer with annual plan discount (2 months free) |\n| Square API rate limits during Valentine''s surge | Low | High | Pre-import customer data 30 days before holiday; cache locally |\n| Low email deliverability for new SendGrid accounts | Medium | High | Warm IP over 60 days; monitor domain reputation dashboard |\n', '[{"step":"market_focus","decision":"Target independent florists only, not chains","reason":"Chains have enterprise marketing teams; independents have the problem and budget; 19K shops in US alone is sufficient TAM"},{"step":"personalization","decision":"Rule-based personalization over ML","reason":"ML requires large per-shop datasets; florists average 200–800 customers — too small for model training; rule-based achieves 74% accuracy"},{"step":"pricing","decision":"Start at $29 not $19","reason":"Under-pricing signals low quality in B2B; florist owner interviews confirmed $25–$35 acceptable for immediate pain relief"},{"step":"sms_strategy","decision":"Require double opt-in for SMS globally","reason":"TCPA fines up to $1,500/message; compliance is non-negotiable even for US shops; proactive compliance reduces legal risk"},{"step":"pos_integration","decision":"Prioritize Square over Shopify for M2","reason":"68% of surveyed florists use Square POS; Shopify penetration in floristry is under 20%"}]',
 'submitted', 47, NOW() - INTERVAL '30 days', NOW() - INTERVAL '31 days', NOW() - INTERVAL '30 days'),

(7, 11, E'# PetalPush: SMS-First Holiday Marketing for Brick-and-Mortar Florists\n\n## 1. Executive Summary\n\nPetalPush is an SMS-first holiday promotion platform designed for the reality of how local florist customers actually shop: on their phones, last-minute, responding to a timely text. While most florist marketing tools lead with email, PetalPush''s hypothesis—validated with 12 beta florists—is that SMS outperforms email for holiday flowers by 3:1 in conversion rate. The platform auto-generates holiday-specific promotional texts with shop-specific bouquet photos, sends them at statistically optimal windows (Tuesday–Thursday, 10am–noon local time), and measures in-store redemption via unique promo codes. Built for non-technical shop owners, PetalPush requires no website or e-commerce store—just a phone number list and a willingness to take more orders. Priced at $39/month with a 30-day free trial. Target: 1,000 active shops, $468K ARR by Month 18.\n\n## 2. Market Analysis\n\n| Metric | Value | Source |\n|---|---|---|\n| Average florist customer list size | 340 contacts | Beta cohort average (n=12 shops) |\n| Email open rate (floristry) | 19.4% | Mailchimp Industry Benchmarks 2024 |\n| SMS open rate (retail) | 98% | SimpleTexting SMS Marketing Report 2024 |\n| SMS click-through rate (retail promo) | 19–26% | Attentive Mobile Commerce Report |\n| % florist customers who prefer SMS for promos | 58% | PetalPush customer survey, n=320 |\n| Average Valentine''s Day order value | $68 | SAF Floral Purchase Tracker 2024 |\n| Revenue increase for florists with promo tools | +22–34% | SAF seasonal benchmark |\n| US independent florists without SMS marketing | ~15,300 | 81% of 19K total |\n\n## 3. Competitive Landscape\n\n| Competitor | SMS Capability | Holiday Intelligence | Price | Florist-Specific |\n|---|---|---|---|---|\n| EZTexting | Yes | No | $20–$85/mo | No |\n| SimpleTexting | Yes | No | $29–$49/mo | No |\n| Podium | Yes | No | $249–$449/mo | No |\n| Mailchimp | Email only | Basic | $13–$350/mo | No |\n| FloristWare | Basic | No | $49–$89/mo | Yes, but outdated |\n| **PetalPush** | SMS-first + Email | Yes, auto-triggered | $39/mo | Yes |\n\n## 4. Target User Personas\n\n**Persona 1 — Linda, 62, Third-Generation Florist, Cincinnati OH**\nLinda has run her family''s flower shop since 1998 with 2,200 customer entries in an old FileMaker database she exports to Excel. She has tried Mailchimp twice and given up both times. Her peak stress is the 72 hours before Valentine''s Day and Mother''s Day when she''s simultaneously managing inventory, staff, and walk-in orders. She needs marketing that runs itself. Price sensitivity: moderate; she''s willing to pay for something that works.\n\n**Persona 2 — Priya, 34, Florist + Organic Wedding Planner, Portland OR**\nPriya opened her shop 3 years ago and has cultivated 480 loyal customers via Instagram. She uses SMS personally but has never done SMS marketing. She''s tech-comfortable, values brand aesthetics, and wants promotional texts that feel on-brand—not generic "SALE 20% OFF" blasts. She wants customizable templates with her shop''s name, signature flower photos, and a personal sign-off.\n\n**Persona 3 — Tom, 51, Florist, Leeds UK**\nTom''s shop serves a mixed clientele: regular domestic customers and a small corporate gifting account. He''s frustrated that national chains like Interflora capture customers he''d served for years via Google search. He wants a tool that keeps his regulars loyal through personalized seasonal touches. Budget: £25–£35/month.\n\n## 5. Core Features\n\n| Priority | Feature | Description |\n|---|---|---|\n| P0 | Contact Import | Upload CSV or sync from Google Contacts; auto-dedup and format phone numbers |\n| P0 | Holiday Auto-Trigger | Pre-loaded calendar for US + UK; sends promos 7 days and 1 day before each holiday |\n| P0 | SMS Campaign Composer | Template library; drag-and-drop photo + text; character count + link preview |\n| P0 | Optimal Send Time | AI-optimized send window per region; default 10am–noon local time Tuesday–Thursday |\n| P0 | Promo Code Generator | Unique in-store redeem codes per campaign; redemption tracked via simple check-in UI |\n| P1 | Email Companion | Same campaign dispatched as email backup for contacts without mobile numbers |\n| P1 | Opt-Out Management | Automatic STOP/UNSUBSCRIBE handling; TCPA/PECR compliance built-in |\n| P1 | Campaign Performance Dashboard | Delivered, opened, clicked, redeemed per campaign |\n| P1 | Customer Segments | VIP (3+ purchases), Lapsed (6+ months), New (first purchase < 30 days) |\n| P2 | Photo Library | Upload 20 bouquet photos; auto-suggest seasonal images per holiday |\n| P2 | Google Business Integration | Auto-post campaign offer to Google Business Profile |\n| P2 | Two-Way SMS | Customers can text back questions; routed to shop''s SMS inbox in the app |\n\n## 6. Technical Architecture\n\n**SMS Infrastructure**: Twilio Messaging Services with dedicated long codes per shop (reduces spam flagging). A2P 10DLC registration handled automatically during onboarding for US numbers. UK numbers registered via Twilio UK.\n\n**Backend**: Ruby on Rails 7.1 API mode + Sidekiq for background jobs. PostgreSQL for relational data. Redis for job queue and rate limiting.\n\n**Scheduling Engine**: Cron-driven job checks upcoming holidays daily at 6am UTC; calculates local time window per shop ZIP code (Google Time Zone API); enqueues SMS batch via Twilio at optimal window.\n\n**Frontend**: Rails + Hotwire (Turbo + Stimulus) — minimal JavaScript; fast page loads on rural broadband connections common among target shops.\n\n**Compliance Layer**: Opt-out keywords (STOP, QUIT, CANCEL) processed by Twilio webhook → immediately flagged in DB; never messaged again. PECR double opt-in for UK contacts.\n\n**Infrastructure**: Render.com (Rails app + Sidekiq workers), Render PostgreSQL, Redis. $0 → $150/mo infrastructure scale path.\n\n## 7. Business Model\n\n| Plan | Price | Contacts | SMS Included | Extra SMS |\n|---|---|---|---|---|\n| Solo | $39/mo | 500 contacts | 2,000 SMS/mo | $0.018/SMS |\n| Shop | $69/mo | 2,500 contacts | 8,000 SMS/mo | $0.015/SMS |\n\nAnnual plan: 15% discount. At 1,000 Solo shops + 200 Shop plans: $39K + $13.8K = $52.8K MRR = $633K ARR.\n\n## 8. MVP Roadmap\n\n| Milestone | Timeline | Deliverables |\n|---|---|---|\n| M1 | Months 1–2 | Contact import, holiday calendar, SMS send engine, promo codes, opt-out handling |\n| M2 | Months 3–4 | Campaign composer with photo upload, optimal send time, performance dashboard |\n| M3 | Months 5–6 | Email companion, customer segmentation, Google Business integration |\n| M4 | Months 7–9 | Two-way SMS, VIP program automation, API for POS systems, multi-location |\n\n## 9. Success Metrics\n\n| KPI | M3 | M6 | M18 |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Active shops | 100 | 350 | 1,200 |\n| MRR | $4,200 | $14,700 | $50,400 |\n| Avg. SMS open rate | > 85% | > 90% | > 92% |\n| Avg. promo redemption rate | > 12% | > 16% | > 20% |\n| Seasonal revenue uplift per shop | +15% | +22% | +30% |\n| Opt-out rate per campaign | < 2% | < 1.5% | < 1% |\n| NPS | ≥ 50 | ≥ 60 | ≥ 68 |\n\n## 10. Risks & Mitigation\n\n| Risk | Likelihood | Impact | Mitigation |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| A2P 10DLC registration delays (US) | High | High | Pre-register brand + campaign during free trial; buffer 2–3 weeks |\n| SMS deliverability issues (carrier filtering) | Medium | High | Dedicated long codes per shop; comply with 10DLC; avoid spam-trigger words in templates |\n| TCPA class-action risk | Low | Very High | Double opt-in enforced; retain consent records 4 years; legal review before US launch |\n| Shops have low-quality contact lists | High | Medium | Free list audit tool; show "deliverable contact" count before first send |\n| Feature creep pressure from florists | Medium | Medium | Strict roadmap adherence; gather requests into a public roadmap board; batch in quarterly releases |\n', '[{"step":"channel_decision","decision":"Lead with SMS over email","reason":"Beta tests across 12 florist shops showed SMS 3:1 conversion rate over email for same holiday campaigns; leads with strongest value prop"},{"step":"tech_stack","decision":"Rails + Hotwire over React SPA","reason":"Target users access dashboard on slow rural broadband; server-rendered Hotwire pages load 40% faster than SPA on 4G; reduced JS complexity"},{"step":"pricing","decision":"Single feature set, two size tiers","reason":"Florist owners make fast decisions; feature-matrix pricing confuses non-technical buyers; contact volume is the only meaningful differentiator"},{"step":"compliance","decision":"Handle A2P 10DLC registration automatically","reason":"Manually navigating 10DLC is a 3-hour task most shop owners will abandon; automating registration is a key activation unlock"},{"step":"mvp_scope","decision":"Defer two-way SMS to M4","reason":"Inbound SMS requires human monitoring infrastructure; adds operational burden before product-market fit confirmed"}]',
 'submitted', 33, NOW() - INTERVAL '27 days', NOW() - INTERVAL '28 days', NOW() - INTERVAL '27 days'),

(7, 23, E'# SeasonalStem: CRM-Lite for Florist Customer Retention and Holiday Revenue\n\n## 1. Executive Summary\n\nSeasonalStem is a lightweight customer relationship and holiday revenue platform built specifically for independent florists who want to compete on relationship, not just price. Where generic email tools treat every customer the same, SeasonalStem builds a flower preference profile for each customer over time—tracking what arrangements they''ve purchased, for whom (self, partner, mother, corporate), and at what price points—and uses these profiles to generate genuinely personalized holiday messages and product recommendations. The hypothesis is that florist customers who receive personalized, relevant messages convert 2–3x better than those receiving generic blasts. This enables florists to earn more from existing customers without acquiring new ones. Priced at $49/month. Target: 800 shops, $470K ARR by Month 20.\n\n## 2. Market Analysis\n\n| Metric | Value | Source |\n|---|---|---|\n| US flower industry retail value | $9.4B/yr | IBISWorld 2024 |\n| Independent florist share of retail | 38% | IBISWorld |\n| Average customer lifetime (independent florist) | 4.2 years | SAF Customer Loyalty Study |\n| Average annual spend per loyal customer | $124 | SAF |\n| Customer retention rate at shops with CRM | 71% vs 49% | SAF Retention Study 2023 |\n| Revenue per retained customer vs. acquired | 5:1 ratio | SAF |\n| % of independent florists with any CRM | 22% | SAF digital maturity report |\n| Market opportunity (CRM for independents) | ~$110M | 19K shops × $480 avg annual spend |\n\n## 3. Competitive Landscape\n\n| Competitor | Customer Profiling | Holiday Automation | Personalization Depth | Price |\n|---|---|---|---|---|\n| Mailchimp | Minimal | Basic date triggers | Low (merge tags only) | $13–$350/mo |\n| HubSpot Starter | Yes, deep | Manual | High, but complex | $20–$890/mo |\n| FloristWare | Order history | Manual campaigns | Low | $49–$89/mo |\n| Podium | Basic | No | Low (review focus) | $249+/mo |\n| Klaviyo | Yes (e-commerce) | Yes | Medium | $45+/mo |\n| **SeasonalStem** | Flower preference profiles | Auto, holiday-aware | High (profile-driven) | $49/mo |\n\n## 4. Target User Personas\n\n**Persona 1 — Beverly, 57, Florist & Gift Shop Owner, Savannah GA**\nBeverly has 1,400 customers and knows her regulars by name. She handwrites birthday cards for her top 50 clients. She wants to scale that personal touch to all 1,400 without working extra hours. SeasonalStem''s promise—"we make you remember everything about your customers"—resonates immediately. She''s willing to pay $49/month if it replaces her current Constant Contact subscription ($35/mo) and actually works.\n\n**Persona 2 — James, 39, Florist & Corporate Account Manager, Birmingham UK**\nJames serves 280 regular domestic customers and 40 corporate accounts (law firms, estate agents, gyms buying weekly arrangements). His challenge is bifurcated: personal customers need emotional, seasonal messaging; corporate accounts need professional, utilitarian order reminders. He needs a tool that handles both audiences with distinct voice and content without manual segmentation every time.\n\n**Persona 3 — Anna, 31, New Florist Business Owner, Denver CO**\nAnna opened her shop 14 months ago and has grown to 380 customers. She is digitally native, uses Instagram and Square, but hasn''t done structured CRM yet. She wants to start right—building customer preference data from day one so that in 3 years she has a loyalty machine. SeasonalStem''s profile-building from Square order history appeals directly to her forward-thinking approach.\n\n## 5. Core Features\n\n| Priority | Feature | Description |\n|---|---|---|\n| P0 | Customer Preference Profiles | Auto-built from order history: flower types, colors, recipient, price range, occasion |\n| P0 | Holiday Campaign Engine | 12 pre-loaded US/UK holidays; auto-generates personalized message per customer segment |\n| P0 | Email + SMS Dispatch | Campaign send via SendGrid + Twilio; TCPA/PECR compliant opt-in management |\n| P0 | Square POS Sync | Real-time order sync to update preference profiles |\n| P0 | Campaign Templates | 60+ templates with personalization tokens: "{first_name}, your partner loved the pink peonies last year…" |\n| P1 | Gifting Calendar | Tracks who each customer buys for; alerts florist 2 weeks before remembered occasions |\n| P1 | VIP Customer Program | Auto-tags top 10% by spend; send exclusive early-access or premium arrangement previews |\n| P1 | Lapsed Customer Recovery | Auto-campaign to customers with no purchase in 90+ days |\n| P1 | In-Store Redemption Tracking | Promo codes or QR codes scanned at POS; attributed revenue dashboard |\n| P2 | Shopify + Wix Integration | For florists with online stores |\n| P2 | Postcard Mailer (Lob API) | Premium physical touch for VIP customers before major holidays |\n| P2 | Referral Program | Reward customers who refer a new client; trackable via unique referral link |\n\n## 6. Technical Architecture\n\n**Preference Engine**: PostgreSQL JSONB column stores per-customer preference vector: `{flower_types: ["peony", "rose"], colors: ["pink", "white"], recipients: ["partner", "mother"], avg_order_value: 72.50}`. Updated incrementally with each Square sync. Rule-based matching maps preferences to seasonal product recommendations.\n\n**Backend**: Django 4.2 + DRF REST API. Celery + Redis for async tasks (campaign dispatch, POS sync). PostgreSQL 15.\n\n**Frontend**: React 18 + TailwindCSS. Campaign composer with real-time personalization preview (shows example email as if sent to a specific customer).\n\n**POS Integration**: Square Webhooks (payment.completed → preference update pipeline). OAuth 2.0 flow for shop owner authorization.\n\n**Email/SMS**: SendGrid (email marketing + transactional) + Twilio SMS. Unsubscribe webhooks update preference DB within 60 seconds.\n\n**Infrastructure**: AWS (ECS Fargate, RDS PostgreSQL, ElastiCache Redis). Terraform IaC. Target SOC 2 Type I at 18 months for corporate account segment.\n\n## 7. Business Model\n\n| Revenue Stream | Details | Projected Mix |\n|---|---|---|\n| Monthly subscription ($49/mo) | Up to 2,000 contacts; unlimited campaigns | 78% |\n| Overage contacts ($10/mo per 1K) | Above 2,000 contacts | 12% |\n| Postcard mailer ($0.85/card) | Via Lob API; marked up from $0.55 cost | 6% |\n| Annual plan discount (10%) | 2-month free incentive | — |\n\nAt 800 shops: $39,200 MRR base + overages + postcards ≈ $45K MRR = $540K ARR.\n\n## 8. MVP Roadmap\n\n| Milestone | Timeline | Deliverables |\n|---|---|---|\n| M1 | Months 1–2 | Customer CSV import, preference profile builder, holiday email campaigns, basic analytics |\n| M2 | Months 3–4 | Square POS sync, personalization tokens, SMS campaigns, opt-in management |\n| M3 | Months 5–6 | Gifting calendar, VIP program, lapsed customer recovery, promo code redemption tracking |\n| M4 | Months 7–9 | Shopify integration, postcard mailer, referral program, revenue attribution dashboard |\n\n## 9. Success Metrics\n\n| KPI | M4 | M8 | M20 |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Active paying shops | 120 | 400 | 800 |\n| MRR | $6,200 | $21,000 | $45,000 |\n| Avg. personalization score (0–100) | > 60 | > 72 | > 80 |\n| Email open rate vs. generic tools | +25% lift | +35% lift | +40% lift |\n| Repeat purchase rate lift | +12% | +20% | +28% |\n| Customer profile completeness (avg) | 55% | 70% | 82% |\n| Annual revenue per shop (median) | +$8,400 | +$14,200 | +$22,000 |\n\n## 10. Risks & Mitigation\n\n| Risk | Likelihood | Impact | Mitigation |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Florists have minimal purchase history data | High | High | Offer manual preference import interview (10-min wizard at onboarding) as fallback |\n| Square API changes break sync | Medium | High | Webhooks + nightly polling fallback; abstract POS layer for multi-provider support |\n| Personalization perceived as "creepy" by customers | Low | Medium | Opt florists into "soft personalization" tone; avoid overly specific callbacks |\n| $49 price above Mailchimp comparison | Medium | Medium | ROI calculator showing revenue lift at onboarding; 30-day free trial to demonstrate value |\n| Operational cost of Lob postcard API | Low | Low | Postcards are opt-in add-on; zero risk to base subscription margin |\n', '[{"step":"core_hypothesis","decision":"Lead with customer preference profiling as primary differentiator","reason":"No florist tool builds per-customer flower preference profiles; this is a genuine data moat over generic email tools"},{"step":"data_model","decision":"JSONB preference vector over normalized tables","reason":"Preference attributes are dynamic and vary per florist type; JSONB enables flexible schema evolution without migrations for each new attribute"},{"step":"pricing","decision":"$49 flat over $29 entry","reason":"CRM positioning justifies higher price; target is shops with recurring customers (avg 340), not just holiday-blast tools"},{"step":"pos_priority","decision":"Square first, then Shopify","reason":"Square penetration in independent floristry is 65%+; Shopify presence is under 15% in this segment per SAF digital survey"},{"step":"personalization_tone","decision":"Opt-in soft personalization mode","reason":"Florist owners worried about customers feeling tracked; offer choice between personal (preference-based) and generic tone to reduce adoption friction"}]',
 'submitted', 29, NOW() - INTERVAL '20 days', NOW() - INTERVAL '21 days', NOW() - INTERVAL '20 days'),

